# data/overrides.jsonl — MANUAL overrides, applied over the dataset by
# `atrium merge` (overlay wins). This is where hand-captured data lives:
#
#   • the facets LaunchBox doesn't carry — `color` (true=Color/false=B&W) and
#     `mouse` (true=Mouse Required/false=No Mouse);
#   • `maxDepth` — the deepest screen depth (bpp: 1/4/8/16/32) a title tolerates.
#     Some games refuse or crash above it (Dark Castle needs 1-bit; others bomb
#     at 8-bit), so the launcher drops the screen to the closest supported depth
#     <= maxDepth before launching, then restores. Absent = no cap (launch at the
#     current colour depth). This facet has NO metadata source — it's curated
#     here, the canonical "problem games" database. (A later pass will launch each
#     title to discover which need a cap; for now this holds the known ones.)
#   • corrections to anything `atrium enrich` got wrong (e.g. a publisher name);
#   • whole records for titles `enrich` couldn't match (give id+name+app+facets).
#
# Each line is a PARTIAL record keyed by `id` (the slug, e.g. "dark-castle");
# only the fields you set are applied. Pipeline order: harvest -> enrich
# (LaunchBox, fills gaps) -> merge (this file, wins) -> catalog/pict. Lines
# starting with '#' or '//' are ignored.

# --- per-game launch depth (verified in Snow) ---
# maxDepth = run the game at the highest supported depth <= this (the launcher
# SETS the screen there before launch). 1 = needs a 1-bit B&W screen; 8 = does
# colour only at 8-bit (never 16/24-bit), so cap+set to 256 colours.
{"id":"dark-castle","color":false,"maxDepth":1}
{"id":"beyond-dark-castle","color":false,"maxDepth":1}
{"id":"asteroids","color":false,"maxDepth":1}
{"id":"prince-of-persia","color":true,"maxDepth":8}

